\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1.1}{\ignorespaces (Image credit: Remo Tilanius) The view of the Event Horizon Telescope (EHT) from Sgr\nobreakspace {}A*. This interferometric array uses Earth-diameter baselines, operating at $230-315$\nobreakspace {}GHz to attain resolution on order of ${\theta _{\rm res} \sim 10\ \mu }$-arcsec. Baselines to ALMA are shown in red, highlighting it's order of magnitude higher sensitivity. Note that the CARMA station has recently been discontinued, a telescope in Greenland is currently being constructed and there is ongoing investigation into a possible site in Southern Africa.}}{3}{figure.1.1}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1.2}{\ignorespaces GR-MHD simulation of an accretion disk inclined at $30^\circ $ around Sgr\nobreakspace {}A* from \citet {Moscibrodzka_2014}. The dark area in the centre, known as the black hole shadow is the lensed image of the photon ring orbiting the BH. A measurement of it's precise shape is a test of general relativity in the strong field regime. Note that the left-right asymmetry in the image is due to doppler boosting, and that all sides of the accretion disk and photon ring are visible due to lensing. }}{5}{figure.1.2}
