\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.1}{\ignorespaces Illustration depicting the basics of scattering in the weak (left) and strong (right) regimes. In the weak regime, the signal is coherently propagated over an area, $A_{\rm weak} \approx \pi r_{\rm F}^2$, whereas in the strong regime, coherent propagation is split over many areas, each of size $A_{strong} \approx \pi r_{\rm 0}^2$. }}{24}{figure.2.1}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.2}{\ignorespaces The $\lambda ^2$ dependence of scattering kernel size is shown by the solid line. This has been derived from measurements made at $\lambda > 17$\nobreakspace {}cm \cite {Bower_2006}. The dotted line shows the derived intrinsic source size which scales as $\lambda ^{1.44}$. This was derived from measurements in the wavelength range, 2\nobreakspace {}cm\nobreakspace {}$< \lambda < 1.3$\nobreakspace {}mm \citep {Doeleman_2008}. The red circles show major-axis observed sizes of Sgr\nobreakspace {}A$^\star $ and the green points show the derived intrinsic major-axis size. This plot was reproduced from \citet {Doeleman_2008}. }}{26}{figure.2.2}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.3}{\ignorespaces Closure phases recorded in a VLBA + LMT observation of Sgr\nobreakspace {}A$^\star $ at $\lambda = 3.5$\nobreakspace {}mm \cite {Ortiz_2016}. The data points are shown as red circles and blue squares and are only distinguished by the calibrator used. The green envelopes show the $1\sigma $ closure phase prediction induced by scattering-induced substructure. Reproduced from \citet {Ortiz_2016}. }}{30}{figure.2.3}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.4}{\ignorespaces Recorded zenith absorption spectrum in the $160-520$\nobreakspace {}GHz range, taken on Mauna Kea at an altitude of $\approx 4000$\nobreakspace {}m. The data has been fit to a sum of $\rm H_20$ lines, an $\rm H_20$ pseudo-continuum and dry absorption lines. The model has been generated using the \textsc {atm} code (see section\nobreakspace {}\ref {sec:atm_theory}), with the bottom panel showing the residuals. Here `dry' refers to all atmospheric constituents except $\rm H_20$. Reproduced from \citet {Pardo_2001} }}{33}{figure.2.4}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.5}{\ignorespaces A log-log plot of RMS visibility phase versus baseline length for an observation of 1\nobreakspace {}Jy source 0748\nobreakspace {}+\nobreakspace {}240 with VLA at 22\nobreakspace {}GHz over a 90\nobreakspace {}min duration. The open circles show RMS phase as measured whereas the solid squares show the same values with a constant thermal noise contribution of $10^\circ $ subtracted in quadrature. Note that the measured and theoretical Kolmogorov turbulent exponent $\beta $ changes with distance on the phase screen as the viewing configuration transitions from a thick screen ($\beta _{\rm theory} = 5/3$) to a thin screen ($\beta _{\rm theory} = 2/3$) at $r \approx 1$\nobreakspace {}km and from a thin screen to completely uncorrelated regime ($\beta = 0$) beyond the outer scale at $r \approx 6$\nobreakspace {}km. Although these regimes appear distinct, there is continous variation between them. Reproduced from \citet *{Carilli_1997} }}{39}{figure.2.5}
